/*
Event bubbling

👉 When an event happens on an element, it first runs on that element
👉 Then it bubbles up to its parent, then its parent’s parent… all the way to the root

EXAMPLE===>
document.getElementById("parent").addEventListener("click", () => {
  console.log("Parent clicked");
});

document.getElementById("child").addEventListener("click", () => {
  console.log("Child clicked");
});

Output:
Child clicked
Parent clicked

 
Why did this happen?===> logic behind this  {Events always start from the target element and bubble upward}
 
[Click Button]
     ↓
Child (runs first)
     ↓
Parent
     ↓
Document


** How to Stop Bubbling
document.getElementById("child").addEventListener("click", (e) => {
  e.stopPropagation();
  console.log("Child clicked");
});


*/

/*
Event Delegation

👉 Event delegation means attaching a single event listener to a parent element to handle events for its child elements.

It works because of event bubbling (events move upward).

EXAMPLE 
❌ (bad approach):
document.getElementById("btn1").addEventListener("click", handler);
document.getElementById("btn2").addEventListener("click", handler);
document.getElementById("btn3").addEventListener("click", handler);

Use this ✅:
document.getElementById("parent").addEventListener("click", handler);


 */

/*
EVENT CAPTURING
👉 Event capturing is the phase where the event travels from the top (root) of the DOM down to the target element before reaching it.

It’s the first phase of event propagation

QUESTION --> Are event capturing and bubbling opposite to each other??

ANSWER --> they’re opposite in direction—but they’re part of the same event flow, not completely separate things.

Every DOM event goes through 3 phases:

1. Capturing   (top → down)
2. Target      (on the element)
3. Bubbling    (bottom → up)



EXAMPLE--->
grandparent.addEventListener("click", () => {
  console.log("Grandparent Capture");
}, true);

parent.addEventListener("click", () => {
  console.log("Parent Bubble");
});

child.addEventListener("click", () => {
  console.log("Child");
});
👉 When you click on child 

OUTPUT->>
Grandparent Capture
Child
Parent Bubble


1. Capturing Phase (top → down)
grandparent has { capture: true }
So it runs first

✔️ Output:

Grandparent Capture

2. Target Phase
Event reaches the actual clicked element → child

✔️ Output:

Child

3. Bubbling Phase (bottom → up)
Now event goes upward
parent has default listener (bubbling)

✔️ Output:

Parent Bubble

